{"id":"physics/0204001","submitter":"Alexey Mazur","authors":"Alexey K. Mazur","title":"DNA Dynamics in A Water Drop","comments":"4 two-column pages, 2 integrated eps plates, RevTeX4","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.bio-ph physics.chem-ph q-bio.BM","license":null,"abstract":"  Due to its polyionic character the DNA double helix is stable and\nbiologically active only in salty aqueous media where its charge is compensated\nby solvent counterions. Monovalent metal ions are ubiquitous in DNA environment\nand they are usually considered as the possible driving force of\nsequence-dependent modulations of DNA structure that make it recognizable by\nproteins. In an effort to directly examine this hypothesis, MD simulations of\nDNA in a water drop surrounded by vacuum were carried out, which relieves the\nrequirement of charge neutrality. Surprisingly, with zero concentration of\ncounterions a dodecamer DNA duplex appears metastable and its structure remains\nsimilar to that observed in experiments.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 1 Apr 2002 15:03:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
{"id":"physics/0204005","submitter":"James Lindesay","authors":"Carramah J. Quiett, James V. Lindesay, Donald R. Lyons","title":"The Design Of Fiber Optic Sensors For Measuring Hydrodynamic Parameters","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.optics physics.flu-dyn","license":null,"abstract":"  We present an approximate analytic model that has been developed for\nexamining hydrodynamic flow near the surface of a fiber optic sensor. An\nanalysis of the conservation of momentum, the continuity equation and the\nNavier-Stokes equation for compressible flow was used to develop expressions\nfor the velocity and the density as a function of the distance along the flow\nand above a two dimensional flat surface. When examining the flow near the\nsurface, these expressions can be used to estimate the sensitivity required to\nperform direct optical measurements and to parameterize the shear force for\nindirect optical measurements. The use of these results allows for direct\nmodeling of sensors using the optical properties of the flow field. Future work\nincludes analyzing the optical parametric design of fiber optic sensors,\nmodeling sensors to utilize those parameters for optimal measurements involving\ndifferent mixtures of fluid flow.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 31 Mar 2002 19:33:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
{"id":"quant-ph/0204002","submitter":"Tsao Chang","authors":"Tsao Chang","title":"Parity Violation and a Preferred Frame","comments":"12 pages, Latex","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Based on parity violation in the weak interaction and evidences from neutrino\noscillation, a natural choice is that neutrinos may be spacelike particles with\na tiny mass. To keep causality for spacelike particles, a kinematic time under\na non-standard form of the Lorentz transformation is introduced, which is\nrelated to a preferred frame. A Dirac-type equation for spacelike neutrinos is\nfurther investigated and its solutions are discussed. This equation can be\nwritten in two spinor equations coupled together via nonzero mass while\nrespecting maximum parity violation. As a consequence, parity violation implies\nthat the principle of relativity is violated in the weak interaction.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 31 Mar 2002 21:50:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
